  <h2>Blues Scale</h2>
  <p>The traditional blues scale is a hexatonic scale, meaning it consists of six notes. It is often formed by adding a diminished fifth (or augmented fourth), commonly known as the "blue note," to the pentatonic scale. The basic structure of the blues scale can be represented as follows:
</p>
<p>
  Root (R): The fundamental note around which the scale is built.
  </p>
  <p>
  Minor Third (b3): A lowered third degree relative to the major scale, contributing to the minor quality.
  </p>
  <p>
  Fourth (4): The regular fourth degree.
  </p>
  <p>
  Diminished Fifth/Blue Note (#4/b5): The distinctive "blue note" that gives the scale its characteristic sound. It falls between the perfect fourth and perfect fifth, contributing to the bluesy, expressive feel.
  </p>
  <p>
  Fifth (5): The regular fifth degree.
  </p>
  <p>
  Minor Seventh (b7): A lowered seventh degree, emphasizing the dominant seventh chord and adding a bluesy flavor.</p>
  <div data-controller="majorblues">

    <section id="instructions">
      <select id="scale-selector">
        <option value="C">C Blues </option>
        <option value="D">D Blues </option>
        <option value="E">E Blues </option>
        <option value="F">F Blues </option>
        <option value="G">G Blues </option>
        <option value="A">A Blues </option>
        <option value="B">B Blues </option>
      </select>
    </section>

    <div id="grid-container"></div>
    <button id="play-btn">Play</button>
    <button id="stop-btn">Stop</button>
    <label for="bpm-slider">BPM:</label>
    <input type="range" id="bpm-slider" min="60" max="200" value="120">
    <span id="bpm-value">120 BPM</span>
  </div>
